@startuml state-user-lifecycle
title trawhile — User Lifecycle

[*] --> Pending : System Admin\ncreates invitation record;\nusers row created\n(SR-F006.F01)

Pending --> Pending : expiry extended\n(SR-F011.F01)

Pending --> Active : OIDC login matches\npending email;\nGDPR notice acknowledged;\nuser_profile created\n(SR-F060.F01, SR-F060.F02)

state Active {
    Active : tracks time, views reports,\nmanages account, uses MCP
}

Pending --> ReadyForScrubbing : invitation expires\n(SR-C010.C01)\nor is withdrawn\n(SR-F007.F01)

Active --> ReadyForScrubbing : user self-anonymises\n(SR-F047.F01) or System Admin\nremoves user (SR-F008.F01)

state "Ready for Scrubbing" as ReadyForScrubbing {
    ReadyForScrubbing : entry / stop active tracking session
    ReadyForScrubbing : entry / delete node_authorizations
    ReadyForScrubbing : entry / delete pending_invitations (if exists)
    ReadyForScrubbing : entry / delete user_profile (if exists;\n  cascade: user_oauth_providers, quick_access)
    ReadyForScrubbing : entry / revoke active mcp_tokens
    ReadyForScrubbing : [users row + time_records (0..n)\n  and requests (0..n) may remain]
}

note right of ReadyForScrubbing
  Cleanup is atomic — single transaction (SR-F070.F01).
  Exits as soon as no time_records or requests remain.
  Immediate for pending users (no records or requests possible).
  May wait for SR-F050.F02 purge for anonymised users.
end note

ReadyForScrubbing --> [*] : users row deleted

@enduml
